          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;"><strong>🇬🇧 UK:</strong> ​​At the upcoming <a href="https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-43715079" target="_blank">Commonwealth</a> summit in Samoa, many nations are preparing to <a href="https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/cd6vy79p750o" target="_blank">discuss reparations</a> for the transatlantic slave trade despite the UK’s opposition. A draft communique suggests a push for further research and discussions on reparatory justice, including financial reparations and other acknowledgment forms. Caribbean nations are particularly vocal, pressing the UK for an apology and reparations. The UK government maintains that reparations are not on the summit’s agenda and prefers focusing on current challenges like climate change.</p>
